# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hvac-control-systems
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] An **air handler**, or **air handling unit** (often abbreviated to **AHU**), is a device used to regulate and circulate air as part of a heating, ventilating, and air-conditioning (HVAC) system.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] An air handler is usually a large metal box containing a blower, furnace or A/C elements, filter racks or chambers, sound attenuators, and dampers.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] Air handlers usually connect to a ductwork ventilation system that distributes the conditioned air through the building and returns it to the AHU, sometimes exhausting air to the atmosphere and bringing in fresh air.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] Sometimes AHUs discharge (*supply*) and admit (*return*) air directly to and from the space served without ductwork.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] Small air handlers, for local use, are called **terminal units**, and may only include an air filter, coil, and blower; these simple terminal units are called blower coils or fan coil units.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] A larger air handler that conditions 100% outside air, and no recirculated air, is known as a **makeup air unit** (**MAU**) or **fresh air handling unit** (**FAHU**).
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] An air handler designed for outdoor use, typically on roofs, is known as a **packaged unit** (**PU**), **heating and air conditioning unit** (**HCU**), **rooftop unit** (**RTU**) or **roof mounted packaged unit** (**RMPU**).
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] The air handler is normally constructed around a framing system with metal infill panels as required to suit the configuration of the components.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] In its simplest form the frame may be made from metal channels or sections, with single skin metal infill panels.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] The metalwork is normally galvanized for long term protection.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] For outdoor units some form of weatherproof lid and additional sealing around joints is provided.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] Larger air handlers will be manufactured from a square section steel framing system with double skinned and insulated infill panels.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] Such constructions reduce heat loss or heat gain from the air handler, as well as providing acoustic attenuation.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] Larger air handlers may be several meters long and are manufactured in a *sectional* manner and therefore, for strength and rigidity, steel section base rails are provided under the unit.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] Where supply and extract air is required in equal proportions for a balanced ventilation system, it is common for the supply and extract air handlers to be joined together, either in a *side-by-side* or a *stacked* configuration.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] But, the first method is very common in the HVAC market.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] The major types of components are described here in approximate order, from the return duct (input to the AHU), through the unit, to the supply duct (AHU output).
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] Air filtration is almost always present in order to provide clean dust-free air to the building occupants.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] It may be via simple low-MERV pleated media, HEPA, electrostatic, or a combination of techniques.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] Gas-phase and ultraviolet air treatments may be employed as well.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] Filtration is typically placed first in the AHU in order to keep all the downstream components clean.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] Depending upon the grade of filtration required, typically filters will be arranged in two (or more) successive banks with a coarse-grade panel filter provided in front of a fine-grade bag filter, or other "final" filtration medium.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] The panel filter is cheaper to replace and maintain, and thus protects the more expensive bag filters.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] The life of a filter may be assessed by monitoring the pressure drop through the filter medium at design air volume flow rate.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] This may be done by means of a visual display using a pressure gauge, or by a pressure switch linked to an alarm point on the building control system.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] Failure to replace a filter may eventually lead to its collapse, as the forces exerted upon it by the fan overcome its inherent strength, resulting in collapse and thus contamination of the air handler and downstream ductwork.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] Air handlers may need to provide hot air, cold air, or both to change the supply air temperature, and humidity level depending on the location and the application.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] Such conditioning is provided by heat exchanger coils within the air handling unit air stream, and such coils may be *direct* or *indirect* in relation to the medium providing the heating or cooling effect.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] Direct heat exchangers include those for gas-fired or fuel oil-burning heaters or a refrigeration evaporator, placed directly in the air stream.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] Electric resistance heaters and heat pumps can be used as well.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] Evaporative cooling is more practical in dry climates, especially if relative humidity is well below 50%.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] Indirect coils use hot water or steam for heating, and chilled water or glycol for cooling (prime energy for heating and air conditioning is provided by central plant elsewhere in the building).
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] Coils are typically manufactured from copper for the tubes, with copper or aluminum fins to aid heat transfer.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] Cooling coils will also employ eliminator plates to remove and drain condensate.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] The hot water or steam is provided by a central boiler, and the chilled water is provided by a central chiller.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] Downstream temperature sensors are typically used to monitor and control "off coil" temperatures, in conjunction with an appropriate motorized control valve prior to the coil.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] If dehumidification is required, then the cooling coil is employed to *over-cool* so that the dew point is reached and condensation occurs.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] A heater coil placed after the cooling coil re-heats the air (therefore known as a *re-heat coil*) to the desired supply temperature.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] This process has the effect of reducing the relative humidity level of the supply air.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] In colder climates, where winter temperatures regularly drop below freezing, then *frost coils* or *pre-heat* coils are often employed as a first stage of air treatment to ensure that downstream filters or chilled water coils are protected against freezing.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] The control of the frost coil is such that if a certain off-coil air temperature is not reached then the entire air handler is shut down for protection.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] Humidification is often necessary in colder climates where continuous heating will make the air drier, resulting in uncomfortable air quality and increased static electricity.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] In order to maintain indoor air quality, air handlers commonly have provisions to allow the introduction of outside air into, and the exhausting of air from the building.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] In temperate climates, mixing the right amount of cooler outside air with warmer return air can be used to approach the desired supply air temperature.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] A mixing chamber is therefore used which has dampers controlling the ratio between the return, outside, and exhaust air.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] Air handlers typically employ a large squirrel cage blower driven by an AC induction electric motor to move the air.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] The blower may operate at a single speed, offer a variety of set speeds, or be driven by a variable-frequency drive to allow a wide range of air flow rates.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] Flow rate may also be controlled by inlet vanes or outlet dampers on the fan.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] Some residential air handlers in the USA (central "furnaces" or "air conditioners") use a brushless DC electric motor that has variable speed capabilities.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] Air handlers in Europe and Australia and New Zealand now commonly use backward curve fans without scroll or "plug fans".
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] These are driven using high efficiency EC (electronically commutated) motors with built in speed control.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] The higher the RTU temperature, the slower the air will flow.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] And the lower the RTU temperature, the faster the air will flow.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] Multiple blowers may be present in large commercial air handling units, typically placed at the end of the AHU and the beginning of the supply ductwork (therefore also called "supply fans").
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] They are often augmented by fans in the return air duct ("return fans") pushing the air into the AHU.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] For home AC fans, this can be a major problem: air circulation is greatly reduced at the vents (as wobble is lost energy), efficiency is compromised, and noise is increased.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] Another major problem in fans that are not balanced is longevity of the bearings (attached to the fan and shaft) is compromised.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] This can cause failure to occur long before the bearings' life expectancy.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] Weights can be strategically placed to correct for a smooth spin (for a ceiling fan, trial and error placement typically resolves the problem).
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] Home/central AC fans or other big fans are typically taken to shops, which have special balancers for more complicated balancing (trial and error can cause damage before the correct points are found).
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] The fan motor itself does not typically vibrate.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] A heat recovery device heat exchanger may be fitted to the air handler between supply and extract airstreams for energy savings and increasing capacity.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] Controls are necessary to regulate every aspect of an air handler, such as: flow rate of air, supply air temperature, mixed air temperature, humidity, air quality.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] They may be as simple as an off/on thermostat or as complex as a building automation system using BACnet or LonWorks, for example.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] Common control components include temperature sensors, humidity sensors, sail switches, actuators, motors, and controllers.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] The blowers in an air handler can create substantial vibration and the large area of the duct system would transmit this noise and vibration to the occupants of the building.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] To avoid this, vibration isolators (flexible sections) are normally inserted into the duct immediately before and after the air handler and often also between the fan compartment and the rest of the AHU.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] The rubberized canvas-like material of these sections allows the air handler components to vibrate without transmitting this motion to the attached ducts.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] The fan compartment can be further isolated by placing it on spring suspension, neoprene pads, or hung on spring hangers, which will mitigate the transfer of vibration through the structure.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] The blower in the air handler also generates noise, which should be attenuated before ductwork enters a noise-sensitive room.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] To achieve meaningful noise reduction in a relatively short length, a sound attenuator is used.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] The attenuator is a specialty duct accessory that typically consists of an inner perforated baffle with sound-absorptive insulation.
[src:hvac-control-systems/air-handler] Sound attenuators may take the place of ductwork; conversely, inline attenuators are located close to the blower and have a bellmouth profile to minimize system effects.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] A **chiller** is a machine that removes heat from a liquid coolant via a vapor-compression, adsorption refrigeration, or absorption refrigeration cycles.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] This liquid can then be circulated through a heat exchanger to cool equipment, or another process stream (such as air or process water).
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] As a necessary by-product, refrigeration creates waste heat that must be exhausted to ambience, or for greater efficiency, recovered for heating purposes.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Vapor compression chillers may use any of a number of different types of compressors.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Most common today are the hermetic scroll, semi-hermetic screw, or centrifugal compressors.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] The condensing side of the chiller can be either air or water cooled.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Even when liquid cooled, the chiller is often cooled by an induced or forced draft cooling tower.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Absorption and adsorption chillers require a heat source to function.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Chilled water is used to cool and dehumidify air in mid- to large-size commercial, industrial, and institutional facilities.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Water cooled chillers can be liquid-cooled (through cooling towers), air-cooled, or evaporatively cooled.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Water or liquid-cooled systems can provide efficiency and environmental impact advantages over air-cooled systems.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] The water is then recirculated to the chiller to be recooled.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] These cooling coils transfer sensible heat and latent heat from the air to the chilled water, thus cooling and usually dehumidifying the air stream.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] A typical chiller for air conditioning applications is rated between 50 kW (170 thousand BTU/h) and 7 MW (24 million BTU/h), and at least two manufacturers (York international and LG) can produce chillers capable of up to 21 MW (72 million BTU/h) cooling.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Chilled water temperatures (leaving from the chiller) usually range from 1 to 7 °C (34 to 45 °F), depending upon application requirements.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Commonly, chillers receive water at 12°C (entering temperature), and cool it to 7°C (leaving temperature).
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] When the chillers for air conditioning systems are not operable or they are in need of repair or replacement, emergency chillers may be used to supply chilled water.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Rental chillers are mounted on a trailer so that they can be quickly deployed to the site.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Large chilled water hoses are used to connect between rental chillers and air conditioning systems.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] In industrial applications, chilled water or other coolant liquid from the chiller is pumped through process or laboratory equipment.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Industrial chillers are used for controlled cooling of products, mechanisms and factory machinery in a wide range of industries.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] They are also used to cool high-heat specialized items such as MRI machines and lasers in hospitals, hotels, and campuses.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Chillers for industrial applications can be centralized, where a single chiller serves multiple cooling needs, or decentralized where each application or machine has its own chiller.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] It is also possible to have a combination of both centralized and decentralized chillers, especially if the cooling requirements are the same for some applications or points of use, but not all.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Chilled water is used to cool and dehumidify air in mid- to large-size commercial, industrial, and institutional (CII) facilities.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Liquid chillers can be liquid-cooled, air-cooled, or evaporatively cooled.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Water or liquid-cooled chillers incorporate the use of cooling towers which improve the chillers' thermodynamic effectiveness as compared to air-cooled chillers.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] This is due to heat rejection at or near the air's wet-bulb temperature rather than the higher, sometimes much higher, dry-bulb temperature.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Evaporatively cooled chillers offer higher efficiencies than air-cooled chillers but lower than liquid-cooled chillers.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Liquid-cooled chillers are typically intended for indoor installation and operation and are cooled by a separate condenser water loop and connected to outdoor cooling towers to expel heat to the atmosphere.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Air-cooled and evaporative cooled chillers are intended for outdoor installation and operation.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Air-cooled machines are directly cooled by ambient air being mechanically circulated directly through the machine's condenser coil to expel heat to the atmosphere.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Evaporative cooled machines are similar, except they implement a mist of water over the condenser coil to aid in condenser cooling, making the machine more efficient than a traditional air-cooled machine.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] No remote cooling tower is typically required with either of these types of packaged air-cooled or evaporatively cooled chillers.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Where available, cold water readily available in nearby water bodies might be used directly for cooling, replacing or supplementing cooling towers.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] The deep water source cooling system in Toronto, Ontario, Canada, is an example.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] It uses cold lake water to cool the chillers, which in turn are used to cool city buildings via a district cooling system.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] The return water is used to warm the city's drinking water supply, which is desirable in this cold climate.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Whenever a chiller's heat rejection can be used for a productive purpose, in addition to the cooling function, very high thermal effectiveness is possible.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Current vapor-compression chiller technology is based on the "Reverse-Rankine cycle" known as vapor-compression.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] See the attached diagram which outlines the key components of the chiller system.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] A vapor compression chiller typically uses one of four types of compressor: Reciprocating compression, scroll compression, screw-driven compression, and centrifugal compression are all mechanical machines that can be powered by electric motors, steam, or gas turbines.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] They produce their cooling effect via the reverse-Rankine cycle, also known as vapor-compression.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] With evaporative cooling heat rejection, their coefficients of performance (COPs) are very high; typically 4.0 or more.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Refrigeration compressors are essentially a pump for refrigerant gas.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] The capacity of the compressor, and hence the chiller cooling capacity, is measured in kilowatts input (kW), Horse power input (HP), or volumetric flow (m3/h, ft3/h).
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] The mechanism for compressing refrigerant gas differs between compressors, and each has its own application.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Common refrigeration compressors include reciprocating, scroll, screw, or centrifugal.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] These can be powered by electric motors, steam turbines, or gas turbines.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Compressors can have an integrated motor from a specific manufacturer, or be open drive--allowing the connection to another type of mechanical connection.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Compressors can also be either hermetic (welded closed) or semi-hermetic (bolted together).
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] In recent years, application of variable-speed drive (VSD) technology has increased efficiencies of vapor compression chillers.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] The first VSD was applied to centrifugal compressor chillers in the late 1970s and has become the norm as the cost of energy has increased.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Now, VSDs are being applied to rotary screw and scroll-technology compressors.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Condensers can be air-cooled, liquid-cooled, or evaporative.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] The condenser is a heat exchanger which allows heat to migrate from the refrigerant gas to either water or air.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Air cooled condenser are manufactured from copper tubes (for the refrigerant flow) and aluminium fins (for the air flow).
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Each condenser has a different material cost and they vary in terms of efficiency.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] With evaporative cooling condensers, their coefficients-of-performance (COPs) are very high; typically 4.0 or more.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Air cooled condensers are installed and operated outdoors and are cooled with outside air, that is often forced through the condenser using electric fans.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Water or liquid cooled condensers are cooled with water that is often in turn cooled by a cooling tower.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] The expansion device (TEV) or refrigerant metering device (RMD) restricts the flow of the liquid refrigerant causing a pressure drop that vaporizes some of the refrigerant; this vaporization absorbs heat from nearby liquid refrigerant.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] The RMD is located immediately prior to the evaporator so that the cold gas in the evaporator can absorb heat from the water in the evaporator.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] There is a sensor for the RMD on the evaporator outlet side which allows the RMD to regulate the refrigerant flow based on the chiller design requirement.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Evaporators can be plate type or shell and tube type.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] The evaporator is a heat exchanger which allows the heat energy to migrate from the water stream into the refrigerant gas.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] During the state change of the remaining liquid to gas, the refrigerant can absorb large amounts of heat without changing temperature.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] The thermodynamic cycle of an absorption chiller is driven by a heat source; this heat is usually delivered to the chiller via steam, hot water, or combustion.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Compared to electrically powered chillers, an absorption chiller has very low electrical power requirements – very rarely above 15 kW combined consumption for both the solution pump and the refrigerant pump.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] However, its heat input requirements are large, and its COP is often 0.5 (single-effect) to 1.0 (double-effect).
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] For the same cooling capacity, an absorption chiller requires a much larger cooling tower than a vapor-compression chiller.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] However, absorption chillers, from an energy-efficiency point of view, excel where cheap, low-grade heat or waste heat is readily available.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] In extremely sunny climates, solar energy has been used to operate absorption chillers.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] The single-effect absorption cycle uses water as the refrigerant and lithium bromide as the absorbent.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] It is the strong affinity that these two substances have for one another that makes the cycle work.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] The entire process occurs in almost a complete vacuum.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] **Generator** : After exiting the heat exchanger, the dilute solution moves into the upper shell.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] The solution surrounds a bundle of tubes which carries either steam or hot water.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] The steam or hot water transfers heat into the pool of dilute lithium bromide solution.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] The solution boils, sending refrigerant vapor upward into the condenser and leaving behind concentrated lithium bromide.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] The concentrated lithium bromide solution moves down to the heat exchanger, where it is cooled by the weak solution being pumped up to the generator.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] **Condenser** : The refrigerant vapor migrates through mist eliminators to the condenser tube bundle.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] The refrigerant vapor condenses on the tubes.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] The heat is removed by the cooling water which moves through the inside of the tubes.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] As the refrigerant condenses, it collects in a trough at the bottom of the condenser.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] **Evaporator** : The refrigerant liquid moves from the condenser in the upper shell down to the evaporator in the lower shell and is sprayed over the evaporator tube bundle.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Due to the extreme vacuum of the lower shell [6 mm Hg (0.8 kPa) absolute pressure], the refrigerant liquid boils at approximately 39 °F (4 °C), creating the refrigerant effect.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] **Absorber** : As the refrigerant vapor migrates to the absorber from the evaporator, the strong lithium bromide solution from the generator is sprayed over the top of the absorber tube bundle.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] The strong lithium bromide solution actually pulls the refrigerant vapor into solution, creating the extreme vacuum in the evaporator.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] The absorption of the refrigerant vapor into the lithium bromide solution also generates heat which is removed by the cooling water.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Now the dilute lithium bromide solution collects in the bottom of the lower shell, where it flows down to the solution pump.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] The chilling cycle is now completed and the process begins once again.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Industrial chillers typically come as complete, packaged, closed-loop systems, including the chiller unit, condenser, and pump station with recirculating pump, expansion valve, no-flow shutdown, internal cold water control.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Compressors can be of two types - scroll and screw depending on the budget and the performance expected from a chiller.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] The internal tank helps maintain cold water temperature and prevents temperature spikes from occurring.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Closed-loop industrial chillers recirculate a clean coolant or clean water with condition additives at a constant temperature and pressure to increase the stability and reproducibility of water-cooled machines and instruments.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] The water flows from the chiller to the application's point of use and back.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] If the water temperature differentials between inlet and outlet are high, then a large external water tank would be used to store the cold water.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] The less common open loop industrial chillers control the temperature of a liquid in an open tank or sump by constantly recirculating it.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] The liquid is drawn from the tank, pumped through the chiller and back to the tank.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] In industrial water chillers is the use of water cooling instead of air cooling.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] In this case the condenser does not cool the hot refrigerant with ambient air, but uses water that is cooled by a cooling tower.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] This development allows a reduction in energy requirements by more than 15% and also allows a significant reduction in the size of the chiller, due to the small surface area of the water-based condenser and the absence of fans.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Additionally, the absence of fans allows for significantly reduced noise levels.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Most industrial chillers use refrigeration as the media for cooling, but some rely on simpler techniques such as air or water flowing over coils containing the coolant to regulate temperature.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Water is the most commonly used coolant within process chillers, although coolant mixtures (mostly water with a coolant additive to enhance heat dissipation) are frequently employed.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] For medium to large chillers this should range from 3.5 to 7.0, with higher values meaning higher efficiency.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] In the US, chiller efficiency is often specified in kilowatts per refrigeration ton (kW/RT).
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Process pump specifications that are important to consider include the process flow, process pressure, pump material, elastomer and mechanical shaft seal material, motor voltage, motor electrical class, motor IP rating and pump rating.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] If the cold water temperature is lower than −5 °C, then a special pump needs to be used to be able to pump the high concentrations of ethylene glycol.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Other important specifications include the internal water tank size and materials and full load current.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Control panel features that should be considered when selecting between industrial chillers include the local control panel, remote control panel, fault indicators, temperature indicators, and pressure indicators.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Additional features include emergency alarms, hot gas bypass, city water switchover, and casters.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Demountable chillers are also an option for deployment in remote areas and where the conditions may be hot and dusty.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] If noise levels of the chiller are acoustically unacceptable, noise control engineers will implement sound attenuators to reduce chiller noise levels.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Larger chillers will typically require an array of sound attenuators sometimes known as a silencer bank.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] A vapor-compression chiller uses a refrigerant internally as its working fluid.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Many refrigerants options are available; when selecting a chiller, the application cooling temperature requirements and refrigerant's cooling characteristics need to be matched.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Important parameters to consider are the operating temperatures and pressures.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] There are several environmental factors that concern refrigerants, and also affect the future availability for chiller applications.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] This is a key consideration in intermittent applications where a large chiller may last for 25 years or more.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] Ozone depletion potential (ODP) and global warming potential (GWP) of the refrigerant need to be considered.
[src:hvac-control-systems/chiller] The refrigerants used in the chillers sold in Europe are mainly R410a (70%), R407c (20%) and R134a (10%).
[src:hvac-control-systems/damper-flow] A **damper** is a valve or plate that stops or regulates the flow of air inside a duct, chimney, VAV box, air handler, or other air-handling equipment.
[src:hvac-control-systems/damper-flow] A damper may be used to cut off central air conditioning (heating or cooling) to an unused room, or to regulate it for room-by-room temperature and climate control - for example, in the case of Volume Control Dampers.
[src:hvac-control-systems/damper-flow] Its operation can be manual or automatic.
[src:hvac-control-systems/damper-flow] Manual dampers are turned by a handle on the outside of a duct.
[src:hvac-control-systems/damper-flow] Automatic dampers are used to regulate airflow constantly and are operated by electric or pneumatic motors, in turn controlled by a thermostat or building automation system.
[src:hvac-control-systems/damper-flow] Automatic or motorized dampers may also be controlled by a solenoid, and the degree of air-flow calibrated, perhaps according to signals from the thermostat going to the actuator of the damper in order to modulate the flow of air-conditioned air in order to effect climate control.
[src:hvac-control-systems/damper-flow] In a chimney flue, a damper closes off the flue to keep the weather and animals (e.g. birds) out and warm or cool air in.
[src:hvac-control-systems/damper-flow] This is usually done in the summer, but also may be done in the winter between uses.
[src:hvac-control-systems/damper-flow] In some cases, the damper may also be partly closed to help control the rate of combustion.
[src:hvac-control-systems/damper-flow] The damper may be accessible only by reaching up into the fireplace by hand or with a woodpoker, or sometimes by a lever or knob that sticks down or out.
[src:hvac-control-systems/damper-flow] On a wood-burning stove or similar device, it is usually a handle on the vent duct as in an air conditioning system.
[src:hvac-control-systems/damper-flow] Forgetting to open a damper before beginning a fire can cause serious smoke damage to the interior of a home, if not a house fire.
[src:hvac-control-systems/damper-flow] A zone damper (also known as a **Volume Control Damper** or **VCD**) is a specific type of damper used to control the flow of air in an HVAC heating or cooling system.
[src:hvac-control-systems/damper-flow] In order to improve efficiency and occupant comfort, HVAC systems are commonly divided up into multiple zones.
[src:hvac-control-systems/damper-flow] For example, in a house, the main floor may be served by one heating zone while the upstairs bedrooms are served by another.
[src:hvac-control-systems/damper-flow] In this way, the heat can be directed principally to the main floor during the day and principally to the bedrooms at night, allowing the unoccupied areas to cool down.
[src:hvac-control-systems/damper-flow] Zone dampers as used in home HVAC systems are usually electrically powered.
[src:hvac-control-systems/damper-flow] In large commercial installations, vacuum or compressed air may be used instead.
[src:hvac-control-systems/damper-flow] In either case, the motor is usually connected to the damper via a mechanical coupling.
[src:hvac-control-systems/damper-flow] For electrical zone dampers, there are two principal designs.
[src:hvac-control-systems/damper-flow] In one design, the motor is often a small shaded-pole synchronous motor combined with a rotary switch that can disconnect the motor at either of the two stopping points ("damper open" or "damper closed").
[src:hvac-control-systems/damper-flow] In this way, applying power to the "open damper" terminal causes the motor to run until the damper is open while applying power at the "close damper" terminal causes the motor to run until the damper is closed.
[src:hvac-control-systems/damper-flow] The motor is commonly powered from the same 24 volt AC power source that is used for the rest of the control system.
[src:hvac-control-systems/damper-flow] This allows the zone dampers to be directly controlled by low-voltage thermostats and wired with low-voltage wiring.
[src:hvac-control-systems/damper-flow] Because simultaneous closure of all dampers might harm the furnace or air handler, this style of damper is often designed to only obstruct a portion of the air duct, for example, 75%.
[src:hvac-control-systems/damper-flow] Another style of electrically powered damper uses a spring-return mechanism and a shaded-pole synchronous motor.
[src:hvac-control-systems/damper-flow] In this case, the damper is normally opened by the force of the spring but can be closed by the force of the motor.
[src:hvac-control-systems/damper-flow] Removal of electrical power re-opens the damper.
[src:hvac-control-systems/damper-flow] This style of damper is advantageous because it is "fail safe"; if the control to the damper fails, the damper opens and allows air to flow.
[src:hvac-control-systems/damper-flow] However, in most applications "fail safe" indicates the damper will close upon loss of power thus preventing the spread of smoke and fire to other areas.
[src:hvac-control-systems/damper-flow] These dampers also may allow adjustment of the "closed" position so that they only obstruct, for example, 75% of the air flow when closed.
[src:hvac-control-systems/damper-flow] For vacuum-operated or pneumatically operated zone dampers, the thermostat usually switches the pressure or vacuum on or off, causing a spring-loaded rubber diaphragm to move and actuate the damper.
[src:hvac-control-systems/damper-flow] As with the second style of electrical zone dampers, these dampers automatically return to the default position without the application of any power, and the default position is usually "open", allowing air to flow.
[src:hvac-control-systems/damper-flow] Like the second style of electrical zone damper, these dampers may allow adjustment of the "closed" position.
[src:hvac-control-systems/damper-flow] Highly sophisticated systems may use some form of building automation such as BACnet or LonWorks to control the zone dampers.
[src:hvac-control-systems/damper-flow] The dampers may also support positions other than fully open or fully closed and are usually capable of reporting their current position and, often, the temperature and volume of the air flowing past the smart damper.
[src:hvac-control-systems/damper-flow] Regardless of the style of damper employed, the systems are often designed so that when no thermostat is calling for air, all dampers in the system are opened.
[src:hvac-control-systems/damper-flow] This allows air to continue to flow while the heat exchanger in a furnace cools down after a heating period completes.
[src:hvac-control-systems/damper-flow] Multiple zones can be implemented using either multiple, individually controlled furnaces/air handlers or a single furnace/air handler and multiple zone dampers.
[src:hvac-control-systems/damper-flow] Each approach has advantages and disadvantages.
[src:hvac-control-systems/damper-flow] Pneumatic actuation is preferred for these dampers.
[src:hvac-control-systems/damper-flow] It is easier to provide zone-classified solenoid valves for pneumatic actuation, as compared to electrical actuation.
[src:hvac-control-systems/damper-flow] The physical size of such solenoid valves have come down very considerably over the years.
[src:hvac-control-systems/damper-flow] Fire dampers are fitted where ductwork passes through fire compartment walls and fire curtains as part of a fire control strategy.
[src:hvac-control-systems/damper-flow] In normal circumstances, these dampers are held open by means of fusible links.
[src:hvac-control-systems/damper-flow] When subjected to heat, these links fracture and allow the damper to close under the influence of the integral closing spring.
[src:hvac-control-systems/damper-flow] The links are attached to the damper such that the dampers can be released manually for testing purposes.
[src:hvac-control-systems/damper-flow] The damper is provided with an access door in the adjacent ductworks for the purpose of inspection and resetting in the event of closure.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] Robert Stirling's innovative contribution to the design of hot air engines of 1816 was what he called the 'Economiser'.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] Later known as the regenerator, it stored heat from the hot portion of the engine as the air passed to the cold side, and released heat to the cooled air as it returned to the hot side.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] This innovation improved the efficiency of the Stirling engine enough to make it commercially successful in particular applications, and has since been a component of every air engine that is called a Stirling engine.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] In boilers, economizers are heat exchange devices that heat fluids, usually water, up to but not normally beyond the boiling point of that fluid.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] Economizers are so named because they can make use of the enthalpy in fluid streams that are hot, but not hot enough to be used in a boiler, thereby recovering more useful enthalpy and improving the boiler's efficiency.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] They are a device fitted to a boiler which saves energy by using the exhaust gases from the boiler to preheat the cold water used to fill it (the *feed water*).
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] Steam boilers use large amounts of energy raising feed water to the boiling temperature, converting the water to steam and sometimes superheating that steam above saturation temperature.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] An indirect contact or direct contact condensing economizer will recover the residual heat from the combustion products.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] A series of dampers, an efficient control system, as well as a ventilator, allow all or part of the combustion products to pass through the economizer, depending on the demand for make-up water and/or process water.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] The temperature of the gases can be lowered from the boiling temperature of the fluid to little more than the incoming feed water temperature while preheating that feed water to the boiling temperature.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] High pressure boilers typically have larger economizer surfaces than low pressure boilers.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] Economizer tubes often have projections like fins to increase the heat transfer surface on the combustion gas side.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] On average over the years, boiler combustion efficiency has risen from 80% to more than 95%.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] The efficiency of heat produced is directly linked to boiler efficiency.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] The percentage of excess air and the temperature of the combustion products are two key variables in evaluating this efficiency.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] The combustion of natural gas needs a certain quantity of air in order to be complete, so the burners need a flow of excess air in order to operate.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] Combustion produces water steam, and the quantity depends on the amount of natural gas burned.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] Also, the evaluation of the dew point depends on the excess air.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] Natural gas has different combustion efficiency curves linked to the temperature of the gases and the excess air.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] For example, if the gases are chilled to 38 °C and there is 15% excess air, then the efficiency will be 94%.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] The condensing economizer can thus recover the sensible and latent heat in the steam condensate contained in the flue gases for the process.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] The economizer is made of an aluminium and stainless steel alloy.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] The gases pass through the cylinder, and the water passes through the finned tubes.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] It condenses about 11% of the water contained in the gases.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] The first successful economizer design was used to increase the steam-raising efficiency of the boilers of stationary steam engines.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] It was patented by Edward Green in 1845, and since then has been known as *Green's economiser*.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] It consisted of an array of vertical cast iron tubes connected to a tank of water above and below, between which the boiler's exhaust gases passed.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] This is the reverse arrangement to that usually but not always seen in the fire tubes of a boiler; there the hot gases usually pass through tubes immersed in water, whereas in an economizer the water passes through tubes surrounded by hot gases.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] The most successful feature of Green's design of economizer was its mechanical scraping apparatus, which was needed to keep the tubes free of deposits of soot.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] Economizers were eventually fitted to virtually all stationary steam engines in the decades following Green's invention.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] Some preserved stationary steam engine sites still have their Green's economisers although usually they are not used.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] One such preserved site is the Claymills Pumping Engines Trust in Staffordshire, England, which is in the process of restoring one set of economisers and the associated steam engine which drove them.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] Another such example is the British Engineerium in Brighton & Hove, where the economiser associated with the boilers for Number 2 Engine is in use, complete with its associated small stationary engine.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] A third site is Coldharbour Mill Working Wool Museum, where the Green's economiser is in working order, complete with the drive shafts from the Pollit and Wigzell steam engine.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] Modern-day boilers, such as those in coal-fired power stations, are still fitted with economizers which are descendants of Green's original design.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] In this context they are often referred to as feedwater heaters and heat the condensate from turbines before it is pumped to the boilers.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] Economizers are commonly used as part of a heat recovery steam generator (HRSG) in a combined cycle power plant.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] In an HRSG, water passes through an economizer, then a boiler and then a superheater.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] The economizer also prevents flooding of the boiler with liquid water that is too cold to be boiled given the flow rates and design of the boiler.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] A common application of economizers in steam power plants is to capture the waste heat from boiler stack gases (flue gas) and transfer it to the boiler feedwater.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] This raises the temperature of the boiler feedwater, lowering the needed energy input, in turn reducing the firing rates needed for the rated boiler output.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] Economizers lower stack temperatures which may cause condensation of acidic combustion gases and serious equipment corrosion damage if care is not taken in their design and material selection.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] A building's HVAC (heating, ventilating, and air conditioning) system can make use of an **air-side economizer** to save energy in buildings by using cool outside air as a means of cooling the indoor space.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] When the temperature of the outside air is less than the temperature of the recirculated air, conditioning with the outside air is more energy efficient than conditioning with recirculated air.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] When the outside air is both sufficiently cool and sufficiently dry (depending on the climate) the amount of enthalpy in the air is acceptable and no additional conditioning of it is needed; this portion of the air-side economizer control scheme is called *free cooling*.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] Air-side economizers can reduce HVAC energy costs in cold and temperate climates while also potentially improving indoor air quality, but are most often not appropriate in hot and humid climates.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] With the appropriate controls, economizers can be used in climates which experience various weather systems.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] When the outside air's dry- and wet-bulb temperatures are low enough, a **water-side economizer** can use water cooled by a wet cooling tower or a dry cooler (also called a fluid cooler) to cool buildings without operating a chiller.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] They are historically known as the *strainer cycle*, but the water-side economizer is not a true thermodynamic cycle.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] Also, instead of passing the cooling tower water through a strainer and then to the cooling coils, which causes fouling, more often a plate-and-frame heat exchanger is inserted between the cooling tower and chilled water loops.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] Good controls, and valves or dampers, as well as maintenance, are needed to ensure proper operation of the air- and water-side economizers.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] A common form of refrigeration economizer is a "walk-in cooler economizer" or "outside air refrigeration system".
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] In such a system outside air that is cooler than the air inside a refrigerated space is brought into that space and the same amount of warmer inside air is ducted outside.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] The resulting cooling supplements or replaces the operation of a compressor-based refrigeration system.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] If the air inside a cooled space is only about 5 °F warmer than the outside air that replaces it (that is, the ∆T>5 °F) this cooling effect is accomplished more efficiently than the same amount of cooling resulting from a compressor based system.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] If the outside air is not cold enough to overcome the refrigeration load of the space the compressor system will need to also operate, or the temperature inside the space will rise.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] Another use of the term occurs in industrial refrigeration, specifically vapor-compression refrigeration.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] The condensing unit would include a compressor and a coil and fans to exchange heat with the ambient air.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] An economizer display takes advantage of the fact that refrigeration systems have increasing efficiencies at increasing pressures and temperatures.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] The power the gas compressor needs is strongly correlated to both the ratio and the difference, between the discharge and the suction pressures (as well as to other features like the refrigerant's heat capacity and the type of compressor).
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] Low temperature systems such as freezers move less fluid in same volumes.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] That means the compressor's pumping is less efficient on low temperature systems.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] This phenomenon is notorious when taking in account that the evaporation temperature for a walk-in freezer at −20 °F (−29 °C) may be around −35 °F (−37 °C).
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] Systems with economizers aim to produce part of the refrigeration work on high pressures, condition in which gas compressors are normally more efficient.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] The economizer concept is linked to subcooling as the condensed liquid line temperature is usually higher than that on the evaporator, making it a good place to apply the notion of increasing efficiencies.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] Recalling the walk-in freezer example, the normal temperature of the liquid line in that system is around 60 °F (16 °C) or even higher (it varies depending on the condensing temperature).
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] That condition is by far less hostile to produce refrigeration, than the evaporator at −35 °F (−37 °C).
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] Several configurations of the refrigeration cycle incorporate an economizer, and benefit from this idea.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] The design of these systems requires expertise and extra components.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] Pressure drop, electronic valve control, and oil drag, must all be considered.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] A system is said to be a two staged set-up if two gas compressors work together in serial to produce the compression.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] A normal booster installation is a two staged system that receives fluid to cool down the discharge of the first compressor, before it is input to the second compressor.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] The fluid that arrives at the interstage of both compressors comes from the liquid line and is normally controlled by expansion, pressure and solenoid valves.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] A standard two staged cycle of this kind has an expansion valve that expands and modulates the amount of refrigerant incoming at the interstage.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] As the fluid arriving at the interstage expands, it will tend to evaporate, producing a temperature drop and cooling the second compressor's suction when mixed with the fluid discharged by the first compressor.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] This kind of set-up may have a heat exchanger between the expansion and the interstage, which may be a second evaporator to produce an additional refrigeration effect, though not as cool as the main evaporator (for example to produce air conditioning or for keeping fresh products).
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] A two staged system is said to be set-up as a booster with subcooling, if the refrigerant arriving at the interstage passes through a subcooling heat exchanger that subcools the main liquid line arriving at the main evaporator of the same system.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] The need to use two compressors in a booster set-up tends to increase the cost of a refrigeration system.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] A two staged system also needs synchronization, pressure control and lubrication.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] To reduce these costs, specialized equipment has been developed.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] Economizer screw compressors are built by several manufacturers like Refcomp, Mycom, Bitzer and York.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] These machines merge both compressors of a two staged system into one screw compressor with two inputs: the main suction and an interstage side entrance for higher pressure gas.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] This means there is no need to install two compressors and still benefit from the booster concept.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] There are two types of economizer setups for these compressors, flash and subcooling.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] The latter works like a two staged booster with subcooling.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] The flash economizer is different because it doesn't use a heat exchanger to produce the subcooling.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] Instead, it has a flash chamber or tank, in which flash gas is produced to lower the temperature of the liquid before the expansion.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] The flash gas that is produced in this tank leaves the liquid line and goes to the economizer entrance of the screw compressor.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] The above systems produce an economizer effect by using compressors, meters, valves and heat exchangers within the refrigeration cycle.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] In some refrigeration systems the economizer can be an independent refrigeration mechanism.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] Such is the case of subcooling the liquid line by any other means that draws the heat out of the main system.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] For example, a heat exchanger that preheats cold water needed for another process or human use, may take heat from the liquid line, effectively subcooling it and increasing the system's capacity.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] Recently, machines exclusively designed for this purpose have been developed.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] In Chile, the manufacturer EcoPac Systems developed a cycle optimizer able to stabilize the temperature of the liquid line and allow either an increase in the refrigeration capacity of the system, or a reduction of the power consumption.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] Such systems have the advantage of not interfering with the original design of the refrigeration system and are a way to expand a single staged system that does not possess an economizer compressor.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] Subcooling may also be produced by superheating the gas leaving the evaporator and heading to the gas compressor.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] These systems withdraw heat from the liquid line and heat up the gas compressor's suction line.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] This is a very common solution to ensure that gas reaches the compressor and liquid reaches the valve.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] It also allows maximum heat exchanger use as minimizes the portion of the heat exchangers used to change the temperature of the fluid, and maximizes the volume in which the refrigerant changes its phase (phenomena involving much more heat flow, the base principle of vapor-compression refrigeration).
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] An internal heat exchanger is simply a heat exchanger that uses the cold gas leaving the evaporator coil to cool the high-pressure liquid that is headed into the beginning of the evaporator coil via an expansion device.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] The gas is used to chill a chamber that normally has a series of pipes for the liquid running through it.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] The superheated gas then proceeds on to the compressor.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] The subcooling term refers to cooling the liquid below its boiling point.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] 10 °F (5.6 °C) of subcooling means it is 10 °F colder than boiling at a given pressure.
[src:hvac-control-systems/economizer] As it represents a difference of temperatures, the subcooling value is not measured on an absolute temperature scale, only on a relative scale as a temperature difference.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] The three major functions of heating, ventilation, and air conditioning are intertwined.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] HVAC systems can provide ventilation and maintain pressure relationships between spaces.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] The means of air delivery and removal from spaces is known as room air distribution.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] In modern buildings, the design, installation, and control systems of these functions are integrated into one or more HVAC systems.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] For very small buildings, contractors normally estimate the capacity and type of system needed and then design the system, selecting the appropriate refrigerant and various components needed.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] For larger buildings, building service designers, mechanical engineers, or building services engineers analyze, design, and specify the HVAC systems.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Specialty mechanical contractors and suppliers then fabricate, install, and commission the systems.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Building permits and code-compliance inspections of the installations are normally required for all sizes of buildings.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Although HVAC is executed in individual buildings or other enclosed spaces (like NORAD's underground headquarters), the equipment involved is in some cases an extension of a larger district heating (DH) or district cooling (DC) network, or a combined DHC (District-Heating-Cooling) network.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] In such cases, the operating and maintenance aspects are simplified, and metering becomes necessary to bill for the energy that is consumed and, in some cases, energy that is returned to the larger system.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] For example, at a given time, one building may be utilizing chilled water for air conditioning, and the warm water it returns may be used in another building for heating or for the overall heating-portion of the DHC network (likely with energy added to boost the temperature).
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] HVAC is based on inventions and discoveries made by Nikolay Lvov, Michael Faraday, Rolla C.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Carpenter, Willis Carrier, Edwin Ruud, Reuben Trane, James Joule, William Rankine, Sadi Carnot, Alice Parker and many others.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Coyne College was the first school to offer HVAC training in 1899.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] The first residential AC was installed by 1914, and by the 1950s there was "widespread adoption of residential AC".
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Heating is the process of transferring thermal energy to an enclosed space in order to raise or maintain its temperature for the comfort of its occupants.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] In central heating systems, a central source such as a boiler, furnace, or heat pump supplies thermal energy at a central location, and air, water, or steam transfers that energy to the spaces to be heated, where it is delivered by convection, radiation, or both.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Small space heaters may also be used to heat individual rooms.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Heaters exist for various types of fuel, including solid fuels, liquids, and gases.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Another type of heat source is electricity, normally heating ribbons composed of high resistance wire (see Nichrome).
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] This principle is also used for baseboard heaters and portable heaters.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Electrical heaters are often used as backup or supplemental heat for heat pump systems.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] The heat pump gained popularity in the 1950s in Japan and the United States.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Heat pumps can extract heat from various sources, such as environmental air, exhaust air from a building, or from the ground.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Heat pumps transfer heat from outside the structure to the air inside.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Initially, heat pump HVAC systems were only used in moderate climates, but with improvements in low temperature operation and reduced loads due to more efficient homes, they are increasing in popularity in cooler climates.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] They can also operate in reverse to cool an interior.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] In the case of heated water or steam, piping is used to transport the heat to the rooms.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Most modern hot water boiler heating systems have a circulator, which is a pump, to move hot water through the distribution system (as opposed to older gravity-fed systems).
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] The heat can be transferred to the surrounding air using radiators, hot water coils (hydro-air), or other heat exchangers.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] The radiators may be mounted on walls or installed within the floor to produce floor heat.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] The use of water as the heat transfer medium is known as hydronics.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] The heated water can also supply an auxiliary heat exchanger to supply hot water for bathing and washing.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Warm air systems distribute the heated air through ductwork systems of supply and return air through metal or fiberglass ducts.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Many systems use the same ducts to distribute air cooled by an evaporator coil for air conditioning.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] The air supply is normally filtered through air filters to remove dust and pollen particles.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] The use of furnaces, space heaters, and boilers as a method of indoor heating can result in incomplete combustion and the emission of carbon monoxide, nitrogen oxides, formaldehyde, volatile organic compounds, and other combustion byproducts.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Incomplete combustion occurs when there is insufficient oxygen; the inputs are fuels containing various contaminants and the outputs are harmful byproducts, such as carbon monoxide, a tasteless and odorless gas with serious adverse health effects.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Ventilation is the process of changing or replacing air in any space to control the temperature or remove any combination of moisture, odors, smoke, heat, dust, airborne bacteria, or carbon dioxide, and to replenish oxygen.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Different methods, such as natural ventilation through windows and mechanical ventilation systems, can be used depending on the building design and air quality needs.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Ventilation often refers to the intentional delivery of outside air to an indoor space to maintain acceptable air quality in buildings.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] The effectiveness of ventilation depends on both indoor and outdoor air quality conditions, as well as on factors such as health impacts and energy demand.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Where outdoor air pollution would degrade indoor air quality, additional treatment measures, such as air filtration, may be necessary.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Methods for ventilating a building may be divided into *mechanical/forced* and *natural* types.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Mechanical, or forced, ventilation is provided by an air handler (AHU) and used to control indoor air quality.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Excess humidity, odors, and contaminants can often be controlled via dilution or replacement with outside air.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] However, in humid climates more energy is required to remove excess moisture from ventilation air.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Kitchens and bathrooms typically have mechanical exhausts to control odors and sometimes humidity.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Factors in the design of such systems include the flow rate (which is a function of the fan speed and exhaust vent size) and noise level.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Direct drive fans are available for many applications and can reduce maintenance needs.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] In summer, ceiling fans and table/floor fans circulate air within a room for the purpose of reducing the perceived temperature by increasing evaporation of perspiration on the skin of the occupants.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Because hot air rises, ceiling fans may be used to keep a room warmer in the winter by circulating the warm stratified air from the ceiling to the floor.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Natural ventilation is the ventilation of a building with outside air without using fans or other mechanical systems.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] It can be via operable windows, louvers, or trickle vents when spaces are small and the architecture permits.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] ASHRAE defined Natural ventilation as the flow of air through open windows, doors, grilles, and other planned building envelope penetrations, and as being driven by natural and/or artificially produced pressure differentials.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Natural ventilation strategies also include cross ventilation, which relies on wind pressure differences on opposite sides of a building.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] By strategically placing openings, such as windows or vents, on opposing walls, air is channeled through the space to enhance cooling and ventilation.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Cross ventilation is most effective when there are clear, unobstructed paths for airflow within the building.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] In more complex schemes, warm air is allowed to rise and flow out high building openings to the outside (stack effect), causing cool outside air to be drawn into low building openings.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Natural ventilation schemes typically use very little energy, but are sensitive to environmental factors.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] In warm or humid climates, maintaining thermal comfort solely via natural ventilation might not be possible.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Air conditioning systems are used, either as backups or supplements.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Air-side economizers also use outside air to condition spaces, but do so using fans, ducts, dampers, and control systems to introduce and distribute cool outdoor air when appropriate.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] A component of natural ventilation is air change rate or air changes per hour: the hourly rate of ventilation divided by the volume of the space.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] For example, six air changes per hour means an amount of new air, equal to the volume of the space, is added every ten minutes.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] For human comfort, a minimum of four air changes per hour is typical, though warehouses might have only two.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Too high of an air change rate may be uncomfortable, akin to a wind tunnel which has thousands of changes per hour.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] The highest air change rates are for crowded spaces, bars, night clubs, commercial kitchens at around 30 to 50 air changes per hour.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Room pressure can be either positive or negative with respect to outside the room.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Positive pressure occurs when there is more air being supplied than exhausted, and is common to reduce the infiltration of outside contaminants.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Natural ventilation is a factor in reducing the spread of airborne illnesses such as tuberculosis, the common cold, influenza, meningitis or COVID-19.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Opening doors and windows are ways to maximize natural ventilation, making the risk of airborne contagion much lower.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Natural ventilation requires little maintenance and is inexpensive.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Ventilation is measured in terms of Air Changes Per Hour (ACH).
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] As of 2023, the CDC recommends that all spaces have a minimum of 5 ACH.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] For hospital rooms with airborne contagions the CDC recommends a minimum of 12 ACH.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] The challenges in facility ventilation are public unawareness, ineffective government oversight, poor building codes that are based on comfort levels, poor system operations, poor maintenance, and lack of transparency.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] UVC or Ultraviolet Germicidal Irradiation is a function used in modern air conditioners which reduces airborne viruses, bacteria, and fungi, through the use of LED UV light that emits across the evaporator.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Air is guided through the sterilization module’s irradiation range, rendering viruses inactive.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] An air conditioning system, or a standalone air conditioner, provides cooling and/or humidity control for all or part of a building.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Air conditioned buildings often have sealed windows, because open windows would work against the system intended to maintain constant indoor air conditions.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Outside, fresh air is generally drawn into the system by a vent into a mix air chamber for mixing with the space return air.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Then the mixture air enters an indoor or outdoor heat exchanger section where the air is to be cooled down, then be guided to the space creating positive air pressure.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] The percentage of return air made up of fresh air can usually be manipulated by adjusting the opening of this vent.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Typical fresh air intake is about 10% of the total supply air.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Air conditioning and refrigeration are provided through the removal of heat.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Heat can be removed through radiation, convection, or conduction.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] The heat transfer medium is a refrigeration system, such as water, air, ice, and chemicals are referred to as refrigerants.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] A refrigerant is employed either in a heat pump system in which a compressor is used to drive thermodynamic refrigeration cycle, or in a free cooling system that uses pumps to circulate a cool refrigerant (typically water or a glycol mix).
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] The refrigeration cycle uses four essential elements to cool, which are the compressor, condenser, metering device, and evaporator.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] In variable climates, the system may include a reversing valve that switches from heating in winter to cooling in summer.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] By reversing the flow of refrigerant, the heat pump refrigeration cycle is changed from cooling to heating or vice versa.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] This allows a facility to be heated and cooled by a single piece of equipment by the same means, and with the same hardware.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Free cooling systems can have very high efficiencies, and are sometimes combined with seasonal thermal energy storage so that the cold of winter can be used for summer air conditioning.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Common storage mediums include deep aquifers or natural underground rock masses accessed through a cluster of small-diameter boreholes equipped with heat exchangers.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Some systems with small storage capacities are hybrids; they utilize free cooling early in the cooling season and later employ a heat pump to chill the circulation coming from the storage.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] The heat pump is added-in because the storage acts as a heat sink when the system is in cooling (as opposed to charging) mode, causing the temperature to gradually increase during the cooling season.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Some systems include an "economizer mode", which is sometimes called a "free-cooling mode".
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] When economizing, the control system will open (fully or partially) the outside air damper and close (fully or partially) the return air damper.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] This will cause fresh, outside air to be supplied to the system.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] When the outside air is cooler than the demanded cool air, this will allow the demand to be met without using the mechanical supply of cooling (typically chilled water or a direct expansion "DX" unit), thus saving energy.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] The control system can compare the temperature of the outside air vs. return air, or it can compare the enthalpy of the air, as is frequently done in climates where humidity is more of an issue.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] In both cases, the outside air must be less energetic than the return air for the system to enter the economizer mode.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Outside of North America, packaged systems are only used in limited applications involving large indoor space such as stadiums, theatres or exhibition halls.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] An alternative to packaged systems is the use of separate indoor and outdoor coils in split systems.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Split systems are preferred and widely used worldwide except in North America.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] In North America, split systems are most often seen in residential applications, but they are gaining popularity in small commercial buildings.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Split systems are used where ductwork is not feasible or where the space conditioning efficiency is of prime concern.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] The benefits of ductless air conditioning systems include easy installation, no ductwork, and greater zonal control.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] In space conditioning, the duct losses can account for 30% of energy consumption.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] The use of minisplits can result in energy savings in space conditioning as there are no losses associated with ducting.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] With the split system, the evaporator coil is connected to a remote condenser unit using refrigerant piping between an indoor and outdoor unit instead of ducting air directly from the outdoor unit.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Indoor units with directional vents mount onto walls, suspended from ceilings, or fit into the ceiling.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Other indoor units mount inside the ceiling cavity so that short lengths of duct handle air from the indoor unit to vents or diffusers around the rooms.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Split systems are more efficient and the footprint is typically smaller than the package systems.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] On the other hand, package systems tend to have a slightly lower indoor noise level compared to split systems since the fan motor is located outside.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Dehumidification (air drying) in an air conditioning system is provided by the evaporator.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Since the evaporator operates at a temperature below the dew point, moisture in the air condenses on the evaporator coil tubes.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] This moisture is collected at the bottom of the evaporator in a pan and removed by piping to a central drain or onto the ground outside.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] A dehumidifier is an air-conditioner-like device that controls the humidity of a room or building.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] It is often employed in basements that have a higher relative humidity because of their lower temperature (and propensity for damp floors and walls).
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] In food retailing establishments, large open chiller cabinets are highly effective at dehumidifying the internal air.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Conversely, a humidifier increases the humidity of a building.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] The HVAC components that dehumidify the ventilation air deserve careful attention because outdoor air constitutes most of the annual humidity load for nearly all buildings.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] A humidifier is a household appliance or device designed to increase the moisture level in the air within a room or an enclosed space.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] It achieves this by emitting water droplets or steam into the surrounding air, thereby raising the humidity.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] In the home, point-of-use humidifiers are commonly used to humidify a single room, while whole-house or furnace humidifiers, which connect to a home's HVAC system, provide humidity to the entire house.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Medical ventilators often include humidifiers for increased patient comfort.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Large humidifiers are used in commercial, institutional, or industrial contexts, often as part of a larger HVAC system.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Nearly every modern air conditioning system, even small window package units, is equipped with an internal air filter or electrostatic precipitator.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] The filters may range from a lightweight gauze-like material to a heavier-duty pleated mat composed of borosilicate glass fibers.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Filters are typically replaced or washed as conditions warrant.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] For example, a building in a dusty environment or a home with furry pets will need to have the filters changed more often than interior spaces without these dirt loads.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Failure to replace these filters as needed can contribute to a lower heat exchange rate, resulting in wasted energy, shortened equipment life, and higher energy bills.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Low airflow can result in iced-over evaporator coils, which can completely stop airflow.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Additionally, very dirty or plugged filters can cause overheating during a heating cycle, which can result in damage to the system or even fire.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Because an air conditioner moves heat between the indoor coil and the outdoor coil, both must be kept clean.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] This means that, in addition to replacing the air filter at the evaporator coil, it is also necessary to regularly clean the condenser coil.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Failure to keep the condenser clean will eventually result in harm to the compressor because the condenser coil is responsible for discharging both the indoor heat (as picked up by the evaporator) and the heat generated by the electric motor driving the compressor.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] HVAC systems play a key role in improving the energy efficiency of buildings, as the building sector accounts for one of the highest shares of global energy consumption.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Since the 1980s, HVAC equipment manufacturers have focused on improving system efficiency.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Initially, these efforts were driven by rising energy costs, but in recent years, environmental sustainability and stricter efficiency regulations have become the primary motivators.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Additionally, improving HVAC system efficiency can enhance indoor air quality, which may lead to better occupant health, comfort, and productivity.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] In the US, the EPA has imposed tighter restrictions over the years.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] There are several methods for making HVAC systems more efficient.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] In the past, water heating was more efficient for heating buildings and was the standard in the United States.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Today, forced air systems can double for air conditioning and are more popular.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Energy efficiency can be improved in central heating systems by using zoned heating.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] This allows a more granular application of heat, similar to non-central heating systems.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Zones are controlled by multiple thermostats.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] In water heating systems the thermostats control zone valves, and in forced air systems they control zone dampers inside the vents which selectively block the flow of air.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Forecasting is another method of controlling building heating by calculating the demand for heating energy that should be supplied to the building in each time unit.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Ground source, or geothermal, heat pumps are similar to ordinary heat pumps, but instead of transferring heat to or from outside air, they rely on the stable, even temperature of the earth to provide heating and air conditioning.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Many regions experience seasonal temperature extremes, which would require large-capacity heating and cooling equipment to heat or cool buildings.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] A metre below the earth's surface, however, the ground remains at a relatively constant temperature.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Utilizing this large source of relatively moderate temperature earth, a heating or cooling system's capacity can often be significantly reduced.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Although ground temperatures vary according to latitude, at 1.8 metres (6 ft) underground, temperatures generally only range from 7 to 24 °C (45 to 75 °F).
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Photovoltaic solar panels can potentially decrease the operating cost of air conditioning.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Traditional air conditioners run using alternating current, and hence, any direct-current solar power needs to be inverted to be compatible with these units.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] New variable-speed DC-motor units allow solar power to more easily run them since this conversion is unnecessary, and since the motors are tolerant of voltage fluctuations associated with variance in supplied solar power (e.g., due to cloud cover).
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Energy recovery systems sometimes utilize heat recovery ventilation or energy recovery ventilation systems that employ heat exchangers or enthalpy wheels to recover sensible or latent heat from exhausted air.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] This is done by transfer of energy from the stale air inside the home to the incoming fresh air from outside.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] The performance of vapor compression refrigeration cycles is limited by thermodynamics.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] These air conditioning and heat pump devices *move* heat rather than convert it from one form to another, so *thermal efficiencies* do not appropriately describe the performance of these devices.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] The Coefficient of performance (COP) measures performance, but this dimensionless measure has not been adopted.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Instead, the Energy Efficiency Ratio (*EER*) has traditionally been used to characterize the performance of many HVAC systems.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] EER is the Energy Efficiency Ratio based on a 35 °C (95 °F) outdoor temperature.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] To more accurately describe the performance of air conditioning equipment over a typical cooling season a modified version of the EER, the Seasonal Energy Efficiency Ratio (*SEER*), or in Europe the ESEER, is used.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] SEER ratings are based on seasonal temperature averages instead of a constant 35 °C (95 °F) outdoor temperature.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] The current industry minimum SEER rating is 14 SEER.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Engineers have pointed out some areas where efficiency of the existing hardware could be improved.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] For example, the fan blades used to move the air are usually stamped from sheet metal, an economical method of manufacture, but as a result they are not aerodynamically efficient.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] A well-designed blade could reduce the electrical power required to move the air by a third.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Demand-controlled kitchen ventilation (DCKV) is a building controls approach to controlling the volume of kitchen exhaust and supply air in response to the actual cooking loads in a commercial kitchen.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Traditional commercial kitchen ventilation systems operate at 100% fan speed independent of the volume of cooking activity and DCKV technology changes that to provide significant fan energy and conditioned air savings.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] By deploying smart sensing technology, both the exhaust and supply fans can be controlled to capitalize on the affinity laws for motor energy savings, reduce makeup air heating and cooling energy, increasing safety, and reducing ambient kitchen noise levels.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Air cleaning and filtration removes particles, contaminants, vapors and gases from the air.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] The filtered and cleaned air then is used in heating, ventilation, and air conditioning.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Clean air delivery rate (CADR) is the amount of clean air an air cleaner provides to a room or space.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] When determining CADR, the amount of airflow in a space is taken into account.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] For example, an air cleaner with a flow rate of 30 cubic metres (1,000 ft3) per minute and an efficiency of 50% has a CADR of 15 cubic metres (500 ft3) per minute.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Filtration performance determines the fraction of airborne particles, including allergens, bacteria, and fine particulate matter, removed from recirculated air.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] This depends on the size of the particle or fiber, the filter packing density and depth, and the airflow rate.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] The HVAC industry includes equipment manufacturing, system design, installation, operation, maintenance, sales, education, and research.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] UL is an omnibus agency and is not specific to the HVAC industry.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] ISO 16813:2006 is one of the ISO building environment standards.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] It establishes the general principles of building environment design.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] It takes into account the need to provide a healthy indoor environment for the occupants as well as the need to protect the environment for future generations and promote collaboration among the various parties involved in building environmental design for sustainability.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] ISO16813 is applicable to new construction and the retrofit of existing buildings.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] In the United States, federal licensure is generally handled by EPA certified for installation and service of HVAC devices.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Many U.S. states have licensing for boiler operation.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Many HVAC engineers are members of the American Society of Heating, Refrigerating, and Air-Conditioning Engineers (ASHRAE).
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] ASHRAE publishes recognized standards for HVAC design, which are updated every four years.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Another popular society is AHRI, which provides regular information on new refrigeration technology, and publishes relevant standards and codes.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] American design standards are legislated in the Uniform Mechanical Code or International Mechanical Code.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] In certain states, counties, or cities, either of these codes may be adopted and amended via various legislative processes.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] These codes are updated and published by the International Association of Plumbing and Mechanical Officials (IAPMO) or the International Code Council (ICC) respectively, on a 3-year code development cycle.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Typically, local building permit departments are charged with enforcement of these standards on private and certain public properties.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] An **HVAC technician** is a tradesman who specializes in heating, ventilation, air conditioning, and refrigeration.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] HVAC technicians in the US can receive training through formal training institutions, where most earn associate degrees.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Training for HVAC technicians includes classroom lectures and hands-on tasks, and can be followed by an apprenticeship wherein the recent graduate works alongside a professional HVAC technician for a temporary period.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] HVAC techs who have been trained can also be certified in areas such as air conditioning, heat pumps, gas heating, and commercial refrigeration.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] The Chartered Institution of Building Services Engineers is a body that covers the essential Service (systems architecture) that allow buildings to operate.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] It includes the electrotechnical, heating, ventilating, air conditioning, refrigeration and plumbing industries.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] To train as a building services engineer, the typical academic entry requirements include qualifications in mathematics and science, such as GCSEs (A-C) in England or Standard Grades (1-3) in Scotland.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Employers will often want a degree in a branch of engineering, such as building environment engineering, electrical engineering or mechanical engineering.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] To become a full member of CIBSE, and so also to be registered by the Engineering Council UK as a chartered engineer, engineers must also attain an Honours Degree and a master's degree in a relevant engineering subject.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] CIBSE publishes several guides to HVAC design relevant to the UK market, and also the Republic of Ireland, Australia, New Zealand and Hong Kong.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] These guides include various recommended design criteria and standards, some of which are cited within the UK building regulations, and therefore form a legislative requirement for major building services works.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Within the construction sector, it is the job of the building services engineer to design and oversee the installation and maintenance of the essential services such as gas, electricity, water, heating and lighting.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Building Services is part of a sector that has over 51,000 businesses and represents 2–3% of the GDP.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] The Air Conditioning and Mechanical Contractors Association of Australia (AMCA), Australian Institute of Refrigeration, Air Conditioning and Heating (AIRAH), Australian Refrigeration Mechanical Association and CIBSE are responsible.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Asian architectural temperature-control have different priorities than European methods.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] For example, Asian heating traditionally focuses on maintaining temperatures of objects such as the floor or furnishings such as Kotatsu tables and directly warming people, as opposed to the Western focus, in modern periods, on designing air systems.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] The Philippine Society of Ventilating, Air Conditioning and Refrigerating Engineers (PSVARE) along with Philippine Society of Mechanical Engineers (PSME) govern on the codes and standards for HVAC / MVAC (MVAC means "mechanical ventilation and air conditioning") in the Philippines.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] The Indian Society of Heating, Refrigerating and Air Conditioning Engineers (ISHRAE) was established to promote the HVAC industry in India.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] ISHRAE was founded at New Delhi in 1981 and a chapter was started in Bangalore in 1989.
[src:hvac-control-systems/hvac] Between 1989 & 1993, ISHRAE chapters were formed in all major cities in India.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] A **thermostat** is a regulating device component which senses the temperature of a physical system and performs actions so that the system's temperature is maintained near a desired setpoint.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Thermostats are used in any device or system that heats or cools to a setpoint temperature.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Examples include building heating, central heating, air conditioners, HVAC systems, water heaters, as well as kitchen equipment including ovens and refrigerators and medical and scientific incubators.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] In scientific literature, these devices are often broadly classified as thermostatically controlled loads (TCLs).
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Thermostatically controlled loads comprise roughly 50% of the overall electricity demand in the United States.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] A thermostat operates as a "closed loop" control device, as it seeks to reduce the error between the desired and measured temperatures.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Sometimes a thermostat combines both the sensing and control action elements of a controlled system, such as in an automotive thermostat.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] The word thermostat is derived from the Greek words θερμός *thermos*, "hot" and στατός *statos*, "standing, stationary".
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] A thermostat exerts control by switching heating or cooling devices on or off, or by regulating the flow of a heat transfer fluid as needed, to maintain the correct temperature.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] A thermostat can often be the main control unit for a heating or cooling system, in applications ranging from ambient air control to automotive coolant control.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Thermostats regulate temperature across a wide range of residential, commercial, and industrial applications, from household HVAC systems and kitchen appliances to medical incubators and automotive cooling systems.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Thermostats use different types of sensors to measure temperatures and actuate control operations.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Mechanical thermostats commonly use bimetallic strips, converting a temperature change into mechanical displacement, to actuate control of the heating or cooling sources.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Electronic thermostats, instead, use a thermistor or other semiconductor sensor, processing temperature change as electronic signals, to control the heating or cooling equipment.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Conventional thermostats are example of "bang-bang controllers" as the controlled system either operates at full capacity once the setpoint is reached, or keeps completely off.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Although it is the simplest program to implement, such control method requires to include some hysteresis in order to prevent excessively rapid cycling of the equipment around the setpoint.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] As a consequence, conventional thermostats cannot control temperatures very precisely.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Instead, there are oscillations of a certain magnitude, usually 1-2 °C.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Such control is in general inaccurate, inefficient and may induce more mechanical wear; it however, allows for more cost-effective compressors compared to ones with continuously variable capacity.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Another consideration is the time delay of the controlled system.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] To improve the control performance of the system, thermostats can include an "anticipator", which stops heating/cooling slightly earlier than reaching the setpoint, as the system will continue to produce heat for a short while.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Turning off exactly at the setpoint will cause actual temperature to exceed the desired range, known as "overshoot".
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Bimetallic sensors can include a physical "anticipator", which has a thin wire touched on the thermostat.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] When current passes the wire, a small amount of heat is generated and transferred to the bimetallic coil.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] This small amount of heat artificially warms the bimetallic coil, causing it to open the heating contacts slightly before the room air reaches the setpoint, thereby compensating for residual thermal inertia.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Electronic thermostats have an electronic equivalent.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] When higher control precision is required, a PID or MPC controller is preferred.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] However, they are nowadays mainly adopted for industrial purposes, for example, for semiconductor manufacturing factories or museums.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Early technologies included mercury thermometers with electrodes inserted directly through the glass, so that when a certain (fixed) temperature was reached the contacts would be closed by the mercury.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] These were accurate to within a degree of temperature.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Possibly the earliest recorded examples of thermostatic control were built by a Dutch innovator, Cornelis Drebbel (1572–1633), about 1620 in England.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] He invented a mercury thermostat to regulate the temperature of a chicken incubator.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] This is one of the first recorded feedback-controlled devices.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Modern thermostatic control was developed in the 1830s by Andrew Ure (1778–1857), a Scottish chemist.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] The textile mills of the time needed a constant and steady temperature to operate optimally, so Ure designed the bimetallic thermostat, which would bend as one of the metals expanded in response to the increased temperature and cut off the energy supply.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Johnson (1847–1911), of Wisconsin, patented a bi-metal room thermostat in 1883, and two years later sought a patent for the first multi-zone thermostatic control system.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Albert Butz (1849–1905) invented the electric thermostat and patented it in 1886.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] One of the first industrial uses of the thermostat was in the regulation of the temperature in poultry incubators.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Charles Hearson, a British engineer, designed the first modern incubator for eggs, which was taken up for use on poultry farms in 1879.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] This covers only devices which both sense and control using purely mechanical means.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Domestic water and steam based central heating systems have traditionally been controlled by bi-metallic strip thermostats, and this is dealt with later in this article.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Purely mechanical control has been localised steam or hot-water radiator bi-metallic thermostats which regulated the individual flow.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] However, thermostatic radiator valves (TRV) are now being widely used.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Purely mechanical thermostats are used to regulate dampers in some rooftop turbine vents, reducing building heat loss in cool or cold periods.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Some automobile passenger heating systems have a thermostatically controlled valve to regulate the water flow and temperature to an adjustable level.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] In older vehicles the thermostat controls the application of engine vacuum to actuators that control water valves and flappers to direct the flow of air.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] In modern vehicles, the vacuum actuators may be operated by small solenoids under the control of a central computer.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Perhaps the most common example of purely mechanical thermostat technology in use today is the internal combustion engine cooling system thermostat, used to maintain the engine near its optimum operating temperature by regulating the flow of coolant to an air-cooled radiator.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] This type of thermostat operates using a sealed chamber containing a wax pellet that melts and expands at a set temperature.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] The expansion of the chamber operates a rod which opens a valve when the operating temperature is exceeded.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] The operating temperature is determined by the composition of the wax.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Once the operating temperature is reached, the thermostat progressively increases or decreases its opening in response to temperature changes, dynamically balancing the coolant recirculation flow and coolant flow to the radiator to maintain the engine temperature in the optimum range.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] On many automobile engines, including all Chrysler Group and General Motors products, the thermostat does not restrict flow to the heater core.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] The passenger side tank of the radiator is used as a bypass to the thermostat, flowing through the heater core.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] This prevents formation of steam pockets before the thermostat opens, and allows the heater to function before the thermostat opens.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Another benefit is that there is still some flow through the radiator if the thermostat fails.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] A thermostatic mixing valve uses a wax pellet to control the mixing of hot and cold water.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] A common application is to permit operation of an electric water heater at a temperature hot enough to kill *Legionella* bacteria (above 60 °C, 140 °F), while the output of the valve produces water that is cool enough to not immediately scald (49 °C, 120 °F).
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] A wax pellet driven valve can be analyzed through graphing the wax pellet's hysteresis which consists of two thermal expansion curves; extension (motion) vs. temperature increase, and contraction (motion) vs. temperature decrease.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] The spread between the up and down curves visually illustrate the valve's hysteresis; there is always hysteresis within wax driven valves due to the phase transition or phase change between solids and liquids.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Hysteresis can be controlled with specialized blended mixes of hydrocarbons; tight hysteresis is most desired, however some applications require broader ranges.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Wax pellet driven valves are used in anti scald, freeze protection, over-temp purge, solar thermal energy or solar thermal, automotive, and aerospace applications among many others.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Thermostats are sometimes used to regulate gas ovens.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] It consists of a gas-filled bulb connected to the control unit by a slender copper tube (capillary tube).
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] The bulb is normally located at the top of the oven.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] The tube ends in a chamber sealed by a diaphragm.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] As the thermostat heats up, the gas expands applying pressure to the diaphragm which reduces the flow of gas to the burner.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] A pneumatic thermostat is a thermostat that controls a heating or cooling system via a series of air-filled control tubes.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] This "control air" system responds to the pressure changes (due to temperature) in the control tube to activate heating or cooling when required.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] The control air typically is maintained on "mains" at 15-18 psi (although usually operable up to 20 psi).
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Pneumatic thermostats typically provide output/ branch/ post-restrictor (for single-pipe operation) pressures of 3-15 psi which is piped to the end device (valve/ damper actuator/ pneumatic-electric switch, etc.).
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] The pneumatic thermostat was invented by Warren Johnson in 1895 soon after he invented the electric thermostat.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] In 2009, Harry Sim was awarded a patent for a pneumatic-to-digital interface that allows pneumatically controlled buildings to be integrated with building automation systems to provide similar benefits as direct digital control (DDC).
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Water and steam based central heating systems have traditionally had overall control by wall-mounted bi-metallic strip thermostats.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] These sense the air temperature using the differential expansion of two metals to actuate an on/off switch.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Typically the central system would be switched on when the temperature drops below the setpoint on the thermostat, and switched off when it rises above, with a few degrees of hysteresis to prevent excessive switching.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Bi-metallic sensing is now being superseded by electronic sensors.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] A principal use of the bi-metallic thermostat today is in individual electric convection heaters, where control is on/off, based on the local air temperature and the setpoint desired by the user.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] These are also used on air-conditioners, where local control is required.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] This follows the same nomenclature as described in Relay § Terminology and Switch § Contact terminology.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] A thermostat is considered to be activated by thermal energy, thus “normal” refers to the state in which temperature is below the setpoint.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Any leading number stands for number of contact sets, like "1NO", "1NC" for one contact set with two terminals.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] "1CO" will also have one contact set, even if it is a switch-over with three terminals.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] The illustration is the interior of a common two wire heat-only household thermostat, used to regulate a gas-fired heater via an electric gas valve.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Similar mechanisms may also be used to control oil furnaces, boilers, boiler zone valves, electric attic fans, electric furnaces, electric baseboard heaters, and household appliances such as refrigerators, coffee pots and hair dryers.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] The center of the coil is attached to a rotating post attached to lever (1).
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] As the coil gets colder the moving end — carrying (4) — moves clockwise.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] The left side is connected via one wire of a pair to the heater control valve.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Moving contact attached to the bimetal coil.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] It is connected electrically by a second wire of the pair to the thermocouple and the heater's electrically operated gas valve.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] This ensures a good contact when the contact closes.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] It also provides hysteresis to prevent short heating cycles, as the temperature must be raised several degrees before the contacts will open.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] As an alternative, some thermostats instead use a mercury switch on the end of the bimetal coil.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] The weight of the mercury on the end of the coil tends to keep it there, also preventing short heating cycles.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] However, this type of thermostat is banned in many countries due to its highly and permanently toxic nature if broken.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] When replacing these thermostats they must be regarded as chemical waste.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Not shown in the illustration is a separate bimetal thermometer on the outer case to show the actual temperature at the thermostat.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] As illustrated in the use of the thermostat above, all of the power for the control system is provided by a thermopile which is a combination of many stacked thermocouples, heated by the pilot light.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] The thermopile produces sufficient electrical power to drive a low-power gas valve, which under control of one or more thermostat switches, in turn controls the input of fuel to the burner.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Their poor efficiency is acceptable in water heaters, since most of the energy "wasted" on the pilot still represents a direct heat gain for the water tank.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] The Millivolt system also makes it unnecessary for a special electrical circuit to be run to the water heater or furnace; these systems are often completely self-sufficient and can run without any external electrical power supply.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] For tankless "on demand" water heaters, pilot ignition is preferable because it is faster than hot-surface ignition and more reliable than spark ignition.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Some programmable thermostats - those that offer simple "millivolt" or "two-wire" modes - will control these systems.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] The majority of modern heating/cooling/heat pump thermostats operate on low voltage (typically 24 volts AC) control circuits.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] The source of the 24 volt AC power is a control transformer installed as part of the heating/cooling equipment.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] The advantage of the low voltage control system is the ability to operate multiple electromechanical switching devices such as relays, contactors, and sequencers using inherently safe voltage and current levels.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Built into the thermostat is a provision for enhanced temperature control using anticipation.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] A heat anticipator generates a small amount of additional heat to the sensing element while the heating appliance is operating.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] This opens the heating contacts slightly early to prevent the space temperature from greatly overshooting the thermostat setting.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] A mechanical heat anticipator is generally adjustable and should be set to the current flowing in the heating control circuit when the system is operating.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] A cooling anticipator generates a small amount of additional heat to the sensing element while the cooling appliance is not operating.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] This causes the contacts to energize the cooling equipment slightly early, preventing the space temperature from climbing excessively.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Cooling anticipators are generally non-adjustable.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Electromechanical thermostats use resistance elements as anticipators.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Most electronic thermostats use either thermistor devices or integrated logic elements for the anticipation function.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] In some electronic thermostats, the thermistor anticipator may be located outdoors, providing a variable anticipation depending on the outdoor temperature.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Thermostat enhancements include outdoor temperature display, programmability, and system fault indication.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] While such 24 volt thermostats are incapable of operating a furnace when the mains power fails, most such furnaces require mains power for heated air fans (and often also hot-surface or electronic spark ignition) rendering moot the functionality of the thermostat.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] In other circumstances such as piloted wall and "gravity" (fanless) floor and central heaters the low voltage system described previously may be capable of remaining functional when electrical power is unavailable.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] There are no standards for wiring color codes, but convention has settled on the following terminal codes and colors.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] In all cases, the manufacturer's instructions should be considered definitive.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Line voltage thermostats are most commonly used for electric space heaters such as a baseboard heater or a direct-wired electric furnace.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] If a line voltage thermostat is used, system power (in the United States, 120 or 240 volts) is directly switched by the thermostat.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] With switching current often exceeding 40 amperes, using a low voltage thermostat on a line voltage circuit will result at least in the failure of the thermostat and possibly a fire.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Some programmable thermostats are available to control line-voltage systems.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Systems which include a fan (electric furnaces, wall heaters, etc.) must typically use simple on/off controls.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Newer digital thermostats have no moving parts to measure temperature and instead rely on thermistors or other semiconductor devices such as a resistance thermometer (resistance temperature detector).
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Each has an LCD screen showing the current temperature, and the current setting.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Most also have a clock, and time-of-day and even day-of-week settings for the temperature, used for comfort and energy conservation.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Some advanced models have touch screens, or the ability to work with home automation or building automation systems.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Digital thermostats use either a relay or a semiconductor device such as triac to act as a switch to control the HVAC unit.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Units with relays will operate millivolt systems, but often make an audible "click" noise when switching on or off.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] HVAC systems with the ability to modulate their output can be combined with thermostats that have a built-in PID controller to achieve smoother operation.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] There are also modern thermostats featuring adaptive algorithms to further improve the inertia prone system behaviour.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] For instance, setting those up so that the temperature in the morning at 7 a.m. should be 21 °C (69.8 °F), makes sure that at that time the temperature will be 21 °C (69.8 °F), where a conventional thermostat would just start working at that time.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] The algorithms decide at what time the system should be activated in order to reach the desired temperature at the desired time.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Most digital thermostats in common residential use in North America and Europe are programmable thermostats, which will typically provide a 30% energy savings if left with their default programs; adjustments to these defaults may increase or reduce energy savings.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] The programmable thermostat article provides basic information on the operation, selection and installation of such a thermostat.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] With non-zoned (typical residential, one thermostat for the whole house) systems, when the thermostat's R (or Rh) and W terminals are connected, the furnace will go through its start-up procedure and produce heat.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] With zoned systems (some residential, many commercial systems — several thermostats controlling different "zones" in the building), the thermostat will cause small electric motors to open valves or dampers and start the furnace or boiler if it is not already running.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Most programmable thermostats will control these systems.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Depending on what is being controlled, a forced-air air conditioning thermostat generally has an external switch for heat/off/cool, and another on/auto to turn the blower fan on constantly or only when heating and cooling are running.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] The power is supplied by a transformer, and when the thermostat makes contact between the 24 volt power and one or two of the other wires, a relay back at the heating/cooling unit activates the corresponding heat/fan/cool function of the unit(s).
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] A thermostat, when set to "cool", will only turn on when the ambient temperature of the surrounding room is above the set temperature.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Thus, if the controlled space has a temperature normally above the desired setting when the heating/cooling system is off, it would be wise to keep the thermostat set to "cool", despite what the temperature is outside.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] On the other hand, if the temperature of the controlled area falls below the desired degree, then it is advisable to turn the thermostat to "heat".
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Some thermostats can automatically switch between "heat" and "cool" to maintain a desired temperature range.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] This is known in the industry as "auto changeover".
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] The heat pump is a refrigeration based appliance which reverses refrigerant flow between the indoor and outdoor coils.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] This is done by energizing a reversing valve (also known as a "4-way" or "change-over" valve).
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] During cooling, the indoor coil is an evaporator removing heat from the indoor air and transferring it to the outdoor coil where it is rejected to the outdoor air.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] During heating, the outdoor coil becomes the evaporator and heat is removed from the outdoor air and transferred to the indoor air through the indoor coil.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] The reversing valve, controlled by the thermostat, causes the change-over from heat to cool.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Residential heat pump thermostats generally have an "O" terminal to energize the reversing valve in cooling.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Some residential and many commercial heat pump thermostats use a "B" terminal to energize the reversing valve in heating.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] The heating capacity of a heat pump decreases as outdoor temperatures fall.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] At some outdoor temperature (called the balance point) the ability of the refrigeration system to transfer heat into the building falls below the heating needs of the building.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] A typical heat pump is fitted with electric heating elements to supplement the refrigeration heat when the outdoor temperature is below this balance point.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Operation of the supplemental heat is controlled by a second stage heating contact in the heat pump thermostat.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] During heating, the outdoor coil is operating at a temperature below the outdoor temperature and condensation on the coil may take place.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] This condensation may then freeze onto the coil, reducing its heat transfer capacity.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Heat pumps therefore have a provision for occasional defrost of the outdoor coil.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] This is done by reversing the cycle to the cooling mode, shutting off the outdoor fan, and energizing the electric heating elements.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] The electric heat in defrost mode is needed to keep the system from blowing cold air inside the building.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] The elements are then used in the "reheat" function.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Although the thermostat may indicate the system is in defrost and electric heat is activated, the defrost function is not controlled by the thermostat.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Since the heat pump has electric heat elements for supplemental and reheats, the heat pump thermostat provides for use of the electric heat elements should the refrigeration system fail.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] This function is normally activated by an "E" terminal on the thermostat.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] When in emergency heat, the thermostat makes no attempt to operate the compressor or outdoor fan.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] The thermostat should not be located on an outside wall or where it could be exposed to direct sunlight at any time during the day.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] It should be located away from the room's cooling or heating vents or device, yet exposed to general airflow from the room(s) to be regulated.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] An open hallway may be most appropriate for a single zone system, where living rooms and bedrooms are operated as a single zone.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] If the hallway may be closed by doors from the regulated spaces then these should be left open when the system is in use.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] If the thermostat is too close to the source controlled then the system will tend to "short a cycle", and numerous starts and stops can be annoying and in some cases shorten equipment life.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] A multiple zoned system can save considerable energy by regulating individual spaces, allowing unused rooms to vary in temperature by turning off the heating and cooling.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] HVAC systems take a long time, usually one to several hours, to cool down or warm up the space from near outdoor conditions in summer or winter.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] Thus, it is a common practice to set setback temperatures when the space is not occupied (night and/or holidays).
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] On the one hand, compared with maintaining at the original setpoint, substantial energy consumption can be saved.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] On the other hand, compared with turning off the system completely, it avoids room temperature drifting too much from the comfort zone, thus reducing the time of possible discomfort when the space is again occupied.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] New thermostats are mostly programmable and include an internal clock that allows this setback feature to be easily incorporated.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] It has been reported that many thermostats in office buildings are non-functional dummy devices, installed to give tenants' employees an illusion of control.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] These dummy thermostats are in effect a type of placebo button.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] However, these thermostats are often used to detect the temperature in the zone, even though their controls are disabled.
[src:hvac-control-systems/thermostat] This function is often referred to as "lockout".
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] A VAV box is the unit that controls the flow of air.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] The single duct terminal configuration is the simplest, where a VAV box is connected to a single supply air duct that delivers treated air from an air-handling unit (AHU) to the space the box is serving.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] This configuration can deliver air at variable temperatures or air volumes to meet the heating and cooling loads as well as the ventilation rates required by the space.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] Most commonly, VAV boxes are pressure independent, meaning the VAV box uses controls to deliver a constant flow rate regardless of variations in system pressures experienced at the VAV inlet.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] This is accomplished by an airflow sensor that is placed at the VAV inlet which opens or closes the damper within the VAV box to adjust the airflow.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] The difference between a CAV and VAV box is that a VAV box can be programmed to modulate between different flowrate setpoints depending on the conditions of the space.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] The VAV box is programmed to operate between a minimum and maximum airflow setpoint and can modulate the flow of air depending on occupancy, temperature, or other control parameters.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] A CAV box can only operate between a constant, maximum value, or an “off” state.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] This difference means the VAV box can provide tighter space temperature control while using much less energy.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] Another reason why VAV boxes save more energy is that they are coupled with variable-speed drives on fans, so the fans can ramp down when the VAV boxes are experiencing part load conditions.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] It is common for VAV boxes to include a form of reheat, either electric or hydronic heating coils.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] While electric coils operate on the principle of electric resistance heating, whereby electrical energy is converted to heat via electric resistance, hydronic heating uses hot water to transfer heat from the coil to the air.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] The addition of reheat coils allows the box to adjust the supply air temperature to meet the heating loads in the space while delivering the required ventilation rates.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] In some applications it is possible for the space to require such high air-change rates it causes a risk of over-cooling.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] In this scenario, the reheat coils could increase the air temperature to maintain the temperature setpoint in the space.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] This scenario tends to happen during cooling seasons in buildings which have perimeter and interior zones.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] The perimeter zones, with more sun exposure, require a lower supply air temperature from the air-handling unit than the interior zones, which have less sun exposure and tend to stay cooler than the perimeter zones when left un-conditioned.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] With the same supply air temperature being delivered to both zones, the reheat coils must heat the air for the interior zone to avoid over-cooling.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] For a single VAV air handler that serves multiple thermal zones, the flow rate to each zone must be varied as well.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] A VAV **terminal unit**, often called a *VAV box*, is the zone-level flow control device.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] It is basically a calibrated air damper with an automatic actuator.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] The VAV terminal unit is connected to either a local or a central control system.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] Historically, pneumatic control was commonplace, but electronic *direct digital control systems* are popular especially for mid- to large-size applications.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] Hybrid control, for example having pneumatic actuators with digital data collection, is popular as well.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] A common commercial application is shown in the diagram.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] This VAV system consists of a VAV box, ductwork, and four air terminals.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] Control of the system's fan capacity is critical in VAV systems.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] Without proper and rapid flow rate control, the system's ductwork, or its sealing, can easily be damaged by overpressurization.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] In the cooling mode of operation, as the temperature in the space is satisfied, a VAV box closes to limit the flow of cool air into the space.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] As the temperature increases in the space, the box opens to bring the temperature back down.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] The fan maintains a constant static pressure in the discharge duct regardless of the position of the VAV box.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] Therefore, as the box closes, the fan slows down or restricts the amount of air going into the supply duct.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] As the box opens, the fan speeds up and allows more air flow into the duct, maintaining a constant static pressure.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] One of the challenges for VAV systems is providing adequate temperature control for multiple zones with different environmental conditions, such as an office on the glass perimeter of a building vs. an interior office down the hall.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] Dual duct systems provide cool air in one duct and warm air in a second duct to provide an appropriate temperature of mixed supply air for any zone.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] An extra duct, however, is cumbersome and expensive.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] Reheating the air from a single duct, using electric or hot water heating, is often a more cost-effective solution.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] Traditional VAV reheat systems use minimum airflow rates of 30% to 50% the design airflow.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] These airflow minimums are selected to avoid the risk of under-ventilation and thermal comfort issues.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] However, published research supporting the efficacy of this approach is scarce.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] Systems operating at lower minimum airflow ranges (10% to 20% of design airflow) stand to use less fan and reheat coil energy relative to a traditional system, and recent research has shown that thermal comfort and adequate ventilation can still be attained at these lower minimums.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] VAV reheat systems using the higher minimum airflow typically employ a conventional "single maximum" control sequence.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] Under this control sequence, a single cooling maximum airflow setpoint is selected for design cooling conditions.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] The cooling airflow is gradually lowered to the minimum airflow setpoint, where it remains as the space temperature lowers beyond the cooling temperature setpoint.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] When the heating setpoint is reached, the electric or hydronic heating coil is activated and gradually provides more heat until the maximum heating capacity is reached at the design heating temperature.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] Research has shown that using a different, "dual maximum" control sequence can save substantial amounts of energy relative to the conventional "single maximum" control sequence.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] This is accomplished due to the "dual maximum" sequence’s use of lower minimum airflow rates.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] Under this control sequence, the same cooling maximum airflow is selected and is similarly lowered as the space temperature decreases.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] By the time the space temperature drops to the cooling temperature setpoint, the airflow reaches a lower minimum value than that used in the "single maximum" sequence (10% - 20% vs.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] When the space temperature reaches the heating temperature setpoint, the heating coil is activated and increases its electrical power (for electric coils) or hot water valve position (for hydronic coils) while the airflow remains at the minimum setpoint.
[src:hvac-control-systems/variable-air-volume] When the heating coil reaches its maximum heating capacity, upon a further drop in space temperature, the airflow is increased until it reaches a maximum heating airflow setpoint (typically about 50% of the maximum cooling airflow).
